  "prompt": "Why do Indian cities get waterlogged so often?",
  "response": "Indian cities often experience waterlogging due to several interconnected factors:\n\n1. Poor Urban Planning\n- Inadequate drainage infrastructure\n- Lack of proper stormwater management systems\n- Unplanned urban expansion\n- Insufficient investment in infrastructure development\n\n2. Geographical Challenges\n- Low-lying areas prone to flooding\n- High rainfall during monsoon seasons\n- Lack of natural water drainage routes\n- Uneven terrain in many urban regions\n\n3. Infrastructure Issues\n- Blocked and insufficient drainage channels\n- Poorly maintained sewage and stormwater systems\n- Lack of regular cleaning of drainage networks\n- Outdated infrastructure design\n\n4. Environmental Factors\n- Increased concretization reducing natural water absorption\n- Reduced green spaces\n- Encroachment of natural water bodies\n- Climate change leading to more intense rainfall events\n\n5. Rapid Urbanization\n- Unregulated construction\n- Inadequate urban planning\n- Overwhelmed existing infrastructure\n- Unauthorized settlements blocking natural water channels\n\n6. Waste Management Problems\n- Garbage blocking drainage systems\n- Poor waste disposal practices\n- Accumulation of solid waste in water channels\n\nAddressing these issues requires comprehensive urban planning, infrastructure investment, and sustainable development strategies.",
